The Federal Inland Revenue Service (FIRS) has decried a systemic abuse of the pioneer incentive scheme instituted by the Federal Government, which has led to tax revenue leakages for the three tiers of government. The executive chairman, Mr Muhammad Nami, made this known when he received state commissioners for Finance, who paid a courtesy call on him in office at the Revenue House, headquarters of the FIRS in Abuja. The FIRS boss vowed to plug this tax leakage in order to generate more revenue for the three tiers of government. In his remarks, the coordinating director, tax operations group, FIRS, Mr Femi Oluwaniyi,  who expressed appreciation to the state commissioners for finance for their support so far in revenue generation for the federation, decried the indiscriminate tax waivers and incentives  granted to undeserving companies, which he stressed has impacted negatively on revenue generation. He revealed the FIRS has discovered that pioneer status certificates had been issued to companies that were not pioneers in their fields in the real sense, hence undeserving of such status, saying this development has led to loss of considerable tax revenue for the three tiers of government. Oluwaniyi hinted the service was, however, auditing its findings with a view to pressing for the cancellation of pioneer certificates issued to undeserving companies in violation of the law, adding pioneer status otherwise granted outside the law would not enjoy tax relief regardless of the certificate issued to them and owners of such certificates would be requested to regularize their tax positions otherwise they would be sanctioned in accordance with the law. In his response, the leader of the delegation, the Benue State commissioner for Finance, Mr David Olofu, congratulated Nami on his well-deserved appointment and his accomplishments in office so far.